Moose Example Analysis 2014 through 2018

For this example, we have moose abundance data from the TOK region of Alaska. Abundance surveys were performed annually from 2014 through 2018, except for the year 2016, in which no survey was done. Therefore, the data set has five years of data, but 2016 has counts that are all NA. The goal is to obtain an abundance prediction for the total number of moose in the region in the year 2018, the most recent year of the survey. The prediction should be able to leverage both spatial correlation across sites and temporal correlation across years.

There are 182 unique spatial locations (sites) and 5 time points. There is a row in the data set for each space-time point combination for a total of 910 rows. The sites are stratified into a HIGH stratum and a LOW stratum. Throughout the five years, there are a small number of sites (~ 10) that changed stratum. Either a site that was classified as LOW was changed to HIGH, or, vice versa. For this preliminary, we use the classification for all sites from the most recent year, 2018. Therefore, a site that was classified as LOW in 2015 but changed to HIGH in 2018 is a HIGH strata site for this analysis. Strata are analyzed separately, and are allowed to have different means, spatial covariances, and temporal covariances.

The HIGH Stratum

We start with an analysis for the HIGH stratum. The model fit with stlmfit() is a sum with error linear mixed model.

library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(FPSpatioTemp)
moose_temp_high <- read_csv(here("inst",
                                 "data/moose_high_2014_2018.csv"))

## keep only variables that are necessary for analysis
moose_df_high <- moose_temp_high %>%
  select(totalmoosena, SurveyID, Surveyyear, ID,
         Stratname, xcoords, ycoords)

## n unique spatial points and n unique time points.
nspat <- nrow(moose_df_high) / length(unique(moose_df_high$Surveyyear))
ntime <- nrow(moose_df_high) / nrow(unique(cbind(moose_df_high$xcoords, moose_df_high$ycoords)))

## create a variable for what values we want added up for
## abundance
moose_df_high <- moose_df_high %>%
  mutate(yearind = if_else(Surveyyear == 2018, true = 1, false = 0))

The model is then fit with stlmfit(), assuming a sum-with-error covariance with an exponential spatial correlation structure and an AR(1) temporal correlation structure.

fit_obj <- stlmfit(formula = totalmoosena ~ 1, data = moose_df_high,
                   xcoordcol = "xcoords", ycoordcol = "ycoords",
                   tcol = "Surveyyear")
pred_obj <- predict(object = fit_obj, wtscol = "yearind")

We can grab the prediction, standard error, and 90% prediction interval from the output:

library(knitr)
prediction <- pred_obj$totalpred
predvar <- pred_obj$predvar
lb <- pred_obj$lb
ub <- pred_obj$ub
tab_stlmfit <- cbind(prediction, sqrt(predvar), lb, ub)
kable(tab_stlmfit)
lb ub
2287.074 103.7932 2116.349 2457.798

We might also want to examine the spatial and temporal covariance parameters:

plot_sp(fit_obj$data$xcoords, fit_obj$data$ycoords,
        fit_obj$data$Surveyyear, fit_obj$data$totalmoosena)

## only plots sites with two connected points in the data set,
## which isn't really the most useful
plot_t(fit_obj$data$xcoords, fit_obj$data$ycoords,
        fit_obj$data$Surveyyear, fit_obj$data$totalmoosena)

We see that there is a fairly large independent error component ($sigma_nugget_spacetime). The spatial nugget (4.43) is slightly smaller than the spatial partial sill (6.35), though the range for the correlation is very small (0.27). The temporal partial sill (0.20) is approximately equal to the temporal nugget (0.24), and the temporal correlation parameter $rho is weak to moderate (0.34).



Comparison to sptotal

We might be interested in comparing this analysis with an analysis on the 2018 data only with the sptotal package.

moose_df_high_2018 <- moose_df_high %>% dplyr::filter(Surveyyear == 2018)

library(sptotal)
fit_obj_2018 <- slmfit(formula = totalmoosena ~ 1,
                       data = moose_df_high_2018,
                       xcoordcol = "xcoords", ycoordcol = "ycoords",
                       estmethod = "ML")

pred_obj_2018 <- predict(fit_obj_2018)
tab_sptotal <- cbind(pred_obj_2018$FPBK_Prediction, sqrt(pred_obj_2018$PredVar),
                     pred_obj_2018$conf_bounds[1], pred_obj_2018$conf_bounds[2])
tab_combined <- rbind(tab_stlmfit, tab_sptotal)
row.names(tab_combined) <- c("stlmfit", "sptotal")
colnames(tab_combined) <- c("prediction", "se", "90% lb", "90% ub")
kable(tab_combined, digits = 0)
prediction se 90% lb 90% ub
stlmfit 2287 104 2116 2458
sptotal 2385 289 1909 2861

We see that the predictions for the analyses are fairly similar. But, the analysis that incorporates time has a much smaller standard error and, therefore, a more narrow prediction interval.

We can also examine the covariance parameters from the analysis with sptotal:

summary(fit_obj_2018)
## 
## Call:
## totalmoosena ~ 1
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -12.696  -7.946  -1.696   4.304  67.304 
## 
## Coefficients:
##      Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## [1,]  12.6959     0.1592   79.75   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Covariance Parameters:
##              Exponential Model
## Nugget            4.881877e-03
## Partial Sill      1.778521e+02
## Range             2.624799e+00
## 
## Generalized R-squared: -2.220446e-16

We see that, though the partial sill is much larger than the nugget in the sptotal analysis, the range is quite small compared to the scale of the x and y coordinates. Therefore, there is effectively very little estimated spatial autocorrelation for sites that are moderately far apart, as seen in the following plot:

plot(fit_obj_2018)



Comparison to stlmfit() with Added NA

Finally, as a small check to make sure that stlmfit() iw working correctly, we might want to compare the prediction from sptotal on the 2018 data only to the prediction from using stlmfit() but artificially making all counts before 2018 NA. The predictions should be very close, possibly differing slightly because of the different method that parameters are optimized.

moose_df_high_2018 <- moose_df_high %>% dplyr::filter(Surveyyear == 2018)
moose_df_high_before2018 <- moose_df_high %>% dplyr::filter(Surveyyear < 2018)
moose_df_high_before2018$totalmoosena <- NA
moose_df_high_fakemiss <- bind_rows(moose_df_high_before2018,
                                    moose_df_high_2018)

fit_obj_fake <- stlmfit(formula = totalmoosena ~ 1,
                        data = moose_df_high_fakemiss,
                   xcoordcol = "xcoords", ycoordcol = "ycoords",
                   tcol = "Surveyyear")
pred_obj_fake <- predict(object = fit_obj_fake, wtscol = "yearind")

After obtaining the prediction, se, and prediction interval, the following table compares all three approaches (stlmfit() with all data, sptotal with 2018 data, and stlmfit() with NA for all data before 2018):

prediction_fake <- pred_obj_fake$totalpred
predvar_fake <- pred_obj_fake$predvar
lb_fake <- pred_obj_fake$lb
ub_fake <- pred_obj_fake$ub
tab_stlmfit_fake <- cbind(prediction_fake, sqrt(predvar_fake),
                          lb_fake, ub_fake)
tab_all <- rbind(tab_combined, tab_stlmfit_fake)
row.names(tab_all) <- c("stlmfit", "sptotal", "stlmfitNA")
kable(tab_all, digits = 0)
prediction se 90% lb 90% ub
stlmfit 2287 104 2116 2458
sptotal 2385 289 1909 2861
stlmfitNA 2384 292 1905 2864

The predictions from sptotal and stlmfit() with the missing data are very close and the standard errors are fairly close as well.



Differences in Predictions between stlmfit() and sptotal.

We might be interested in which sites seem to have a large difference in predicted abundance between stlmfit() and sptotal. To do so, we can first arrange() the prediction data set from sptotal so that sites have the same order as the data set used in stlmfit(), which orders the observations by year, then xcoordinates, then y coordinates:

sptotal_df <- pred_obj_2018$Pred_df
## drop sites that were sampled
sptotal_df_unsamp <- sptotal_df %>%
  dplyr::filter(totalmoosena_sampind == 0) %>%
  arrange(xcoordsTM_, ycoordsTM_)

Then, we compare the sitewise predictions for each method:

cbind(pred_obj$zhatu, sptotal_df_unsamp$totalmoosena_pred_count)

We see that most sites have similar predicted abundance for the two methods. However, for some sites, the predictions are quite different. For example, site 784 (the sites are identified by the rownumbers) has a prediction of 21.4 moose using stlmfit() and a prediction of 9.7 moose using sptotal. Why are these predictions so drastically different?

test_df <- moose_df_high %>% slice(784) %>% select(ID)
semi_join(moose_df_high, test_df)
## # A tibble: 5 x 8
##   totalmoosena SurveyID Surveyyear ID         Stratname xcoords ycoords yearind
##          <dbl>    <dbl>      <dbl> <chr>      <chr>       <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1           NA      676       2014 6406-14240 HIGH         80.6    167.       0
## 2           NA      708       2015 6406-14240 HIGH         80.6    167.       0
## 3           NA      708       2016 6406-14240 HIGH         80.6    167.       0
## 4           42      836       2017 6406-14240 HIGH         80.6    167.       0
## 5           NA      895       2018 6406-14240 HIGH         80.6    167.       1

We see that, in the year 2017, site 784 was surveyed and there were found to be 42 moose in that year. In 2018, the site was not surveyed, but, the temporal autocorrelation is likely the reason that the prediction is much higher in stlmfit() than it is with sptotal, which ignores data from previous years completely.

Similarly, site 765 has a much higher prediction in stlmfit() than sptotal:

test_df <- moose_df_high %>% slice(765) %>% select(ID)
semi_join(moose_df_high, test_df)
## # A tibble: 5 x 8
##   totalmoosena SurveyID Surveyyear ID         Stratname xcoords ycoords yearind
##          <dbl>    <dbl>      <dbl> <chr>      <chr>       <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1           40      676       2014 6404-14250 HIGH         72.4    163.       0
## 2           NA      708       2015 6404-14250 HIGH         72.4    163.       0
## 3           NA      708       2016 6404-14250 HIGH         72.4    163.       0
## 4           39      836       2017 6404-14250 HIGH         72.4    163.       0
## 5           NA      895       2018 6404-14250 HIGH         72.4    163.       1

and the reason seems for this difference seems similar to the reason for site 784.

Note that the reverse also holds. For example, for site 743, sptotal predicts an abundance of 27.6 moose while stlmfit() predicts an abundance of 12.5 moose.

test_df <- moose_df_high %>% slice(743) %>% select(ID)
semi_join(moose_df_high, test_df)

The LOW Stratum

We can repeat this analysis for the LOW stratum, but, we wont use the fake data set to compare to sptotal in the code below.

Fit model with stlmfit():

library(tidyverse)
moose_df_low <- read_csv(here("inst", "data/moose_low_2014_2018.csv"))

moose_df_low <- moose_df_low %>%
  mutate(yearind = if_else(Surveyyear == 2018, true = 1, false = 0))

fit_obj_low <- stlmfit(formula = totalmoosena ~ 1, data = moose_df_low,
                   xcoordcol = "xcoords", ycoordcol = "ycoords",
                   tcol = "Surveyyear")
pred_obj_low <- predict(object = fit_obj_low, wtscol = "yearind")

Fit model with sptotal:

moose_df_low_2018 <- moose_df_low %>% dplyr::filter(Surveyyear == 2018)
library(sptotal)

fit_obj_low_2018 <- slmfit(formula = totalmoosena ~ 1,
                       data = moose_df_low_2018,
                       xcoordcol = "xcoords", ycoordcol = "ycoords",
                       estmethod = "ML")
pred_obj_low_2018 <- predict(fit_obj_low_2018)



Comparing the Totals Across Strata

We can then add up our predictors and prediction variances across the strata for each method, assuming no cross-covariance across strata:

pred_obj_2018$FPBK_Prediction + pred_obj_low_2018$FPBK_Prediction ## sptotal 2018
##         [,1]
## [1,] 3049.13
pred_obj$totalpred + pred_obj_low$totalpred ## stlmfit
##         [,1]
## [1,] 2751.88
sqrt(pred_obj_2018$PredVar + pred_obj_low_2018$PredVar) ## sptotal 2018
##          [,1]
## [1,] 333.1741
sqrt(pred_obj$predvar + pred_obj_low$predvar) ## stlmfit
##         [,1]
## [1,] 128.457



Moose Analysis 2004 to 2006

As a second data set, well use data from 2004 to 2006 on different sites in the TOK region in Alaska. The data are older, but the primary purpose of this example is just to show that the function can be used on a different real data set.

Comments for this analysis are omitted.

library(tidyverse)
moose_df <- read_csv(here("inst", "data/moose_04_06.csv"))

tm_obj <- sptotal::LLtoTM(mean(moose_df$centrlon),
                          lat = moose_df$centrlat,
                          lon = moose_df$centrlon)

moose_df$xTM <- tm_obj$xy[ ,1]
moose_df$yTM <- tm_obj$xy[ ,2]


moose_df <- moose_df %>%
  mutate(yearind = if_else(Surveyyear == 2006, true = 1, false = 0))

moose_04_06 <- stlmfit(formula = totalmoosena ~ 1, data = moose_df,
                       xcoordcol = "xTM", ycoordcol = "yTM",
                       tcol = "Surveyyear",
                       areacol = NULL)
pred_04_06 <- predict(moose_04_06, wtscol = "yearind")
pred_04_06$totalpred ## pred
##          [,1]
## [1,] 1788.912
sqrt(pred_04_06$predvar) ## se
##         [,1]
## [1,] 48.4315
## compare to sptotal
moose_2006 <- moose_df %>% dplyr::filter(Surveyyear == 2006)
moose_06 <- slmfit(formula = totalmoosena ~ 1, data = moose_2006,
                       xcoordcol = "xTM", ycoordcol = "yTM",
                       areacol = NULL)
predict(moose_06)
## Prediction Info:

## totalmoosena       1793 145.9   1553   2033
##              Numb. Sites Sampled Total Numb. Sites Total Observed
## totalmoosena                  98               187            937
##              Average Density
## totalmoosena           9.561

Finally, the following is just a check to make sure things dont change from re-ordering the data set.

moose_df2 <- moose_df %>% sample_n(nrow(moose_df))

moose_04_06_reorder <- stlmfit(formula = totalmoosena ~ 1,
                               data = moose_df2,
                               xcoordcol = "xTM", ycoordcol = "yTM",
                               tcol = "Surveyyear",
                               areacol = NULL)
pred_04_06_reorder <- predict(moose_04_06_reorder, wtscol = "yearind")
pred_04_06$totalpred; pred_04_06_reorder$totalpred ## pred
